Yes — a small autosave script can make the worksheet feel friendly without ever sending data anywhere.  
Here’s a minimal, privacy‑safe example that keeps everything local to the user’s browser:

```html
<script>
// Store all <textarea> and <input type="text"> content locally
const fields = document.querySelectorAll('textarea, input[type="text"]');
fields.forEach(f => {
  // Load any saved value
  const saved = localStorage.getItem(f.name || f.placeholder);
  if(saved) f.value = saved;
  // Save on change
  f.addEventListener('input', () => {
    localStorage.setItem(f.name || f.placeholder, f.value);
  });
});

// Optional: clear saved data when user clicks a reset button
function clearWorksheet() {
  if(confirm("Clear all locally saved notes? (This cannot be undone.)")){
      fields.forEach(f => localStorage.removeItem(f.name || f.placeholder));
      alert("Local worksheet data cleared.");
  }
}
</script>
```

Add a simple **Reset / Clear Notes** button at the bottom:

```html
<button onclick="clearWorksheet()">Clear saved notes</button>
```

This script:
* Never uploads or shares information.  
* Saves only in the user’s browser (so entries persist after a refresh).  
* Lets users manually clear their own data.

You can label it *“Local autosave—your notes stay on your device only”* to reinforce privacy.  

